{"title_page": "Marek Szmid", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Marek Szmid\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Marek Andrezj Szmid<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|19166|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|3|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Nuneaton]], England<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132001<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=301 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.vn/o6enu |archivedate=17 April 2020 |title=Marek Szmid |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| youthclubs1    = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| years1         = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs1         = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| caps1          = 2\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs2         = [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 2003\n| clubs3         = [[Marine F.C.|Marine]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs4         = [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.|Nuneaton Griff]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs5         = [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]\n| caps5          =\n| goals5         =\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs6         = [[Liverpool John Moores University F.C.|Liverpool John Moores University]]\n| caps6          =\n| goals6         =\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]]\n| caps7          =\n| goals7         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam1  = [[ESFA under-15 football team|ESFA U15]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 15\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20131999\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 8\n| nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 =\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps3  =\n| nationalgoals3 =\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national futsal team|England futsal]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 6\n}}\n'''Marek Andrezj Szmid''' (born 2 March 1982) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]], who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Club career===\nBorn in [[Nuneaton]], Szmid began his career with the youth team of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] which he captained and then went on to make several reserve team appearances, before moving to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in November 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/896023.stm|title=Football Transfers|date=1 August 2002|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531092310/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |title=\"IT'S A GOOD CLUB\" - MAREK SZMID |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |date=17 November 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He made 2 appearances in [[the Football League]] for Southend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/southend/southend.html|title=SOUTHEND UNITED : 1946/47 \u2013 2009/10|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A \u2013 Z Player's Database}}</ref><ref>{{soccerbase|29294}}</ref> Szmid later played non-league football with [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]] and [[Marine F.C.|Marine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004022117/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |archivedate=4 October 2012 |title=Latest Transfers |work=NonLeagueDaily.com |publisher=Baltic Publications Limited |date=29 November 2003 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn the same season he moved to play for [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 10/09/2003</ref> In 2004, he played for [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 04/08/2004</ref> The next season saw him playing for [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]].<ref>Liverpool Echo 06/08/2005</ref> That season saw him suffering a bad injury which caused him to retire from playing football. After retiring, he attended [[Liverpool John Moores University]] where he graduated with a B.A. in Sports Development in 2007.<ref>Liverpool John Moores University 2007 Graduates Award Ceremony</ref> Whilst studying he suffered a severe injury which caused his playing career to stop. The following year he attended the University of Chester where he took part in the GTP (Graduate Teacher Programme).<ref>University of Chester Graduates Award Ceremony 2008</ref> He started teaching Physical Education at Ashton-on-Mersey School in Trafford in 2008.<ref>http://issuu.com/ashton-on-mersey_school/docs/ashton_magazine_2011</ref> In September 2010 he started work as the Assistant Head of Education and Welfare at Manchester United F.C.<ref>http://youblisher.com/p/238592-Man-U-Tour-Diary-2011/</ref>\n\n===International career===\nSzmid represented [[ESFA Under-15|ESFA U-15]] and the team reached 3rd place of the mini World Cup at the Montaigu Tournament in France.<ref>ESFA Handbook 1998/99</ref> He was in the last ESFA Under-15 team, when they beat Germany 1\u20130 at the Olympic Stadium Berlin, before the Football Association took over the running of Schools Football. The following season, he represented [[England Under-16|England U-16]] playing in the UEFA European Championship where they lost in the quarter-final to the Czech Republic who had Petr Cech in goal.<ref>FA Handbook1999/2000</ref>\nSzmid played international futsal for [[England national futsal team|England]], receiving his first call-up in March 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460|title=4 Nations tournament|date=3 March 2005|publisher=Futsal Planet}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20020615003942/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html Marek Szmid] at SouthendUnited.co.uk\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szmid, Marek}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sutton Coldfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Marine F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Griff F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Liverpool John Moores University]]\n[[Category:Vauxhall Motors F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Marek Szmid\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Marek Andrezj Szmid<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|19166|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|3|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Nuneaton]], England<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132001<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=301 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.vn/o6enu |archivedate=17 April 2020 |title=Marek Szmid |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| youthclubs1    = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| years1         = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs1         = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| caps1          = 2\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs2         = [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 2003\n| clubs3         = [[Marine F.C.|Marine]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs4         = [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.|Nuneaton Griff]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs5         = [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]\n| caps5          =\n| goals5         =\n| years6         = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs6         = [[Liverpool John Moores University F.C.|Liverpool John Moores University]]\n| caps6          =\n| goals6         =\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]]\n| caps7          =\n| goals7         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam1  = [[ESFA under-15 football team|ESFA U15]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 15\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20131999\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 8\n| nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 =\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps3  =\n| nationalgoals3 =\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national futsal team|England futsal]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 6\n}}\n'''Marek Andrezj Szmid''' (born 2 March 1982) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]], who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Club career===\nBorn in [[Nuneaton]], Szmid began his career with the youth team of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] which he captained and then went on to make several reserve team appearances, before moving to [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in November 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/896023.stm|title=Football Transfers|date=1 August 2002|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531092310/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~160586,00.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |title=\"IT'S A GOOD CLUB\" - MAREK SZMID |work=SouthendUnited.co.uk |publisher=Southend United Football Club |date=17 November 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> He made 2 appearances in [[the Football League]] for Southend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/southend/southend.html|title=SOUTHEND UNITED : 1946/47 \u2013 2009/10|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A \u2013 Z Player's Database}}</ref><ref>{{soccerbase|29294}}</ref> Szmid later played non-league football with [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]] and [[Marine F.C.|Marine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004022117/http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=14132 |archivedate=4 October 2012 |title=Latest Transfers |work=NonLeagueDaily.com |publisher=Baltic Publications Limited |date=29 November 2003 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn the same season he moved to play for [[Nuneaton Griff F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 10/09/2003</ref> In 2004, he played for [[Nuneaton Town F.C.]].<ref>Coventry Evening Telegraph 04/08/2004</ref> The next season saw him playing for [[Vauxhall Motors F.C.|Vauxhall Motors]].<ref>Liverpool Echo 06/08/2005</ref> That season saw him suffering a bad injury which caused him to retire from playing football. After retiring, he attended [[Liverpool John Moores University]] where he graduated with a B.A. in Sports Development in 2007.<ref>Liverpool John Moores University 2007 Graduates Award Ceremony</ref> Whilst studying he suffered a severe injury which caused his playing career to stop. The following year he attended the University of Chester where he took part in the GTP (Graduate Teacher Programme).<ref>University of Chester Graduates Award Ceremony 2008</ref> He started teaching Physical Education at Ashton-on-Mersey School in Trafford in 2008.<ref>http://issuu.com/ashton-on-mersey_school/docs/ashton_magazine_2011</ref> In September 2010 he started work as the Assistant Head of Education and Welfare at Manchester United F.C.<ref>http://youblisher.com/p/238592-Man-U-Tour-Diary-2011/</ref>\n\n===International career===\nSzmid represented [[ESFA Under-15|ESFA U-15]] and the team reached 3rd place of the mini World Cup at the Montaigu Tournament in France.<ref>ESFA Handbook 1998/99</ref> He was in the last ESFA Under-15 team, when they beat Germany 1\u20130 at the Olympic Stadium Berlin, before the Football Association took over the running of Schools Football. The following season, he represented [[England Under-16|England U-16]] playing in the UEFA European Championship where they lost in the quarter-final to the Czech Republic who had Petr Cech in goal.<ref>FA Handbook1999/2000</ref>\nSzmid played international futsal for [[England national futsal team|England]], receiving his first call-up in March 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futsalplanet.com/news/news-01.asp?id=4460|title=4 Nations tournament|date=3 March 2005|publisher=Futsal Planet}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[[https://web.archive.org/web/20020615003942/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/stats/view/player_profiles/0,,10444~22117,00.html Marek Szmid] at SouthendUnited.co.uk\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szmid, Marek}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sutton Coldfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Marine F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Griff F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nuneaton Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Liverpool John Moores University]]\n[[Category:Vauxhall Motors F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marek_Szmid"}
{"title_page": "Friday the 13th Part 2", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = Friday the 13th Part 2\n| image           = Friday_the_13th_part2.jpg \n| caption         = Theatrical release poster\n| director        = [[Steve Miner]]\n| producer        = Steve Miner\n| writer          = {{plainlist|\n* Ron Kurz\n}}\n| based on        = {{Based on|Characters|[[Victor Miller (writer)|Victor Miller]]}}\n| starring        = {{plainlist| <!--PER BILLING BLOCK-->\n* [[Adrienne King]]\n* [[Amy Steel]]\n* [[John Furey]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Harry Manfredini]]\n| cinematography  = [[Peter Stein (cinematographer)|Peter Stein]]\n| editing         = Susan E. Cunningham\n| studio          = Georgetown Productions\n| distributor     = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released        = {{Film date|1981|4|30}}\n| runtime         = 87 minutes\n| country         = United States\n| language        = English\n| budget          = $1.2 million<ref name=numbers>{{cite web|url=https://the-numbers.com/movie/Friday-the-13th-Part-2#tab=summary|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 (1981)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150924091658/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Friday-the-13th-Part-2%23tab=summary|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross           = $21.7 million<ref name=numbers/>\n}}\n'''''Friday the 13th Part 2'''''{{efn|The film's poster and related marketing use the Roman numeral \"II\". However, the copyright notice and the film's on-screen title use \"Part 2\".}} is a 1981 American [[horror film]] produced and directed by [[Steve Miner]] in his [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]], written by Ron Kurz, and starring [[Amy Steel]] and [[John Furey]]. The film also features the return of [[Adrienne King]], [[Betsy Palmer]] and [[Walt Gorney]], who respectively portrayed [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]], [[Pamela Voorhees]], and [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Crazy Ralph|Crazy Ralph]] in the prior installment. It is the second installment in the [[Friday the 13th (franchise)|''Friday the 13th'' film series]] and a direct sequel to ''[[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' (1980). It picks up five years later, where a new murderer begins stalking the camp counselors at a nearby training camp on Crystal Lake.\n\nOriginally, ''Part 2'' was intended to be part of an [[Anthology film|anthology]] series of films based on the [[Friday the 13th|Friday the 13th superstition]]. However, after the popularity of the original film's surprise ending, the filmmakers opted to continue the story and mythology surrounding Camp Crystal Lake, a trend which would be repeated in every film in the franchise.\n\nLike the original film, ''Part 2'' faced opposition from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]], who noted its \"accumulative violence\" as problematic, resulting in numerous cuts being made to allow an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film ratings|R]] rating. The film was released theatrically in North America on April 30, 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=friday13th2.htm|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121206025552/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=friday13th2.htm|archive-date=December 6, 2012}}</ref> Although it did not gross as much as the original, the sequel grossed $21.7 million in the U.S. on a budget of $1.2 million. A sequel, ''[[Friday the 13th Part III]]'', was released the following year.\n\n== Plot ==\nTwo months after [[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|the murders at Camp Crystal Lake]], sole survivor [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]] is recovering from her traumatic experience. In her apartment, when Alice opens the refrigerator to get her cat some food, she finds the severed head of [[Pamela Voorhees]] in her refrigerator and is murdered by an unknown assailant with an ice pick to her temple.\n\nFive years later, Paul Holt opens a school for camp counselors on the shore of Crystal Lake. The camp is attended by Sandra Dier, her boyfriend Jeff Dunsberry, troublemaker Scott Cheney, tomboy Terry McCarthy, wheelchair-bound Mark Jarvis, sweet-natured Vickie Perry, jokester Ted Bowen, and Paul's assistant [[Ginny (Friday the 13th)|Ginny Field]], as well as many other trainees. Around the campfire that night, Paul tells the counselors about the legend of [[Jason Voorhees]], of how he survived his drowning, grew up living in the woods, and is now seeking to kill any intruders to avenge his mother's death. A man with a spear scares everyone, but it's only Ted in a mask. Paul reassures everyone that Jason is dead and that Camp Crystal Lake is now condemned and off limits. That night, Crazy Ralph wanders onto the property to warn the group but is [[garrote]]d from behind a tree. The following day, Jeff and Sandra sneak off to Camp Crystal Lake and find a carcass before getting caught by Deputy Winslow and returned to the camp. Later, Winslow spots someone masked in a [[burlap sack]] running across the road and chases him into the woods and to a shack before he is killed with a hammer claw.\n\nBack at camp, Paul offers the others one last night on the town before the training begins; six stay behind, including Jeff and Sandra, who are forced to stay as punishment for sneaking off. At the bar, Ginny muses that if Jason were still alive and had witnessed his mother's death, it may have left him with no distinction between life and death, or right and wrong. Paul dismisses the idea, proclaiming that Jason is nothing but an [[urban legend]]. Meanwhile, the assailant appears at the camp and kills the counselors, one by one. Scott has his throat slit with a machete while caught in a rope trap, and Terry is killed off-screen upon finding his dead body. Mark gets the machete slammed into his face and falls down a flight of stairs. The killer then moves upstairs and impales Jeff and Sandra with a spear as they have sex, and then stabs Vickie with a kitchen knife.\n\nLater, Ginny and Paul return to find the place in disarray. In the dark, the killer ambushes Paul and continues to chase Ginny throughout the camp and into the woods, where she comes across the shack. After barricading herself inside, she finds an altar with Pamela Voorhees' head on it, surrounded by a pile of bodies. Realizing that Jason Voorhees is the killer, Ginny puts on Pamela's sweater and tries to psychologically convince Jason that she is his mother. The ruse fails when he spots his mother's head on the altar and attacks Ginny. Paul appears and attacks Jason, but he is quickly overwhelmed. Just as Jason is about to kill Paul with a pickaxe, Ginny picks up the machete and slams it down into Jason's shoulder, seemingly killing him.\n\nPaul and Ginny return to the cabin. They think that Jason has followed them, but when they open the door, they are greeted by Terry's dog, Muffin. Suddenly, an unmasked Jason bursts through the window from behind and grabs Ginny. She then awakens to being loaded into an ambulance. She calls out for Paul, who is nowhere to be seen, his fate left ambiguous. Back in the shack, Pamela Voorhees' head remains on the altar as Jason is also [[Friday the 13th Part III|nowhere to be seen]].\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Anchor|Warrington Gillette}}<!-- until an article is created for him -->\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Amy Steel]] as [[Ginny (Friday the 13th)|Ginny Field]]\n* [[John Furey]] as [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Paul Holt|Paul Holt]]\n* [[Adrienne King]] as [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]]\n* [[Steve Daskewisz]] as [[Jason Voorhees]]\n** Warrington Gillette as Jason Voorhees (unmasked)\n* [[Stuart Charno|Stu Charno]] as Ted Bowen\n* [[Lauren-Marie Taylor]] as Vickie Perry\n* Marta Kober as [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Sandra Dier|Sandra Dier]]\n* [[Tom McBride (actor)|Tom McBride]] as Mark Jarvis\n* [[Bill Randolph]] as Jeff Dunsberry\n* Kirsten Baker as Terry McCarthy\n* [[Russell Todd]] as Scott Cheney\n* [[Walt Gorney]] as [[Crazy Ralph]]\n* [[Betsy Palmer]] as [[Pamela Voorhees]]\n* Jack Marks as Deputy Winslow\n* Cliff Cudney as Max \n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nFollowing the success of ''Friday the 13th'' in 1980, [[Paramount Pictures]] began plans to make a sequel. First acquiring the worldwide distribution rights, Frank Mancuso, Sr. stated, \"We wanted it to be an event, where teenagers would flock to the theaters on that Friday night to see the latest episode.\" The initial ideas for a sequel involved the \"Friday the 13th\" title being used for a series of films, released once a year, that would not have direct continuity with one another but be a separate \"scary movie\" in their own right. Phil Scuderi\u2014one of three owners of Esquire Theaters, along with Steve Minasian and Bob Barsamian, who produced the original film\u2014insisted that the sequel have Jason Voorhees, Pamela's son, even though his appearance in the original film was only meant to be a joke. [[Steve Miner]], associate producer on the first film, believed in the idea and would go on to direct the first two sequels, after Cunningham opted not to return to the director's chair. Miner would use many of the same crew members from the first film while working on the sequels.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|pages=50\u201352}} Cunningham had mixed feelings about the entire \"Friday the 13th\" enterprise that he outlined for film critic and author [[Stephen Hunter]] in an interview for a book Hunter wrote on violent films. Hunter stated that Cunningham \"wasn't particularly proud\" of his work on these films, and Cunningham bluntly said that the only thing that seemed to reach a teenaged audience at that time involved high levels of gore and graphic violence.\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Adrienne King]] was pursued by an obsessed fan after the success of the original ''Friday the 13th'' and purportedly wished her role to be small as possible,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/how-friday-the-13th-star-adrienne-king-uses-her-terrifying-stalker-tale-to-help-her-fans/|title=Friday The 13th\u2019 Star Adrienne King Uses Her Terrifying Stalker Tale To Help Her Fans|publisher=Uproxx|author=Burns, Ashley|accessdate=September 30, 2016}}</ref> though in the documentary ''[[Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th]]'', it was stated that King's agent had asked for a higher salary, which the studio could not afford.<ref name=bd/>\n\nThe film's heroine, Ginny, is played by Amy Steel, who won the part through an audition. \"At the time of [making the film], it was before the genre really picked up so I didn\u2019t give it a lot of credit or take it seriously. For me, it was just another audition because I had no idea what it would end up meaning after all this time. When I played Ginny, I was really young and different from a lot of the people working at the time so that came out in my character. I was naturally suspicious of cocky guys at that age, and you see a lot of that when I\u2019m on screen with Paul (John Furey). I tried to put so much behind the actual words in the script just so she felt almost unreachable, to Paul and to audiences. I wanted her to have some power.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/16108/dread-central-s-final-girls-amy-steel/|work=Dread Central|author=Wixson, Heather|date=March 5, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012501/https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/16108/dread-central-s-final-girls-amy-steel/|archive-date=October 18, 2018|title=Dread Central\u2019s Final Girls: Amy Steel|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nActor Warrington Gillette played Jason unmasked at the end of the film. Stuntman Steve Daskawisz (also known as Steve Dash) was credited as Jason Stunt Double but played the masked Jason throughout the rest of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/3379/dash-steve-friday-the-13th-part-2/|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|author=Dash, Steve|work=Dread Central|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012354/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/3379/dash-steve-friday-the-13th-part-2/|archive-date=October 18, 2018|date=July 1, 2006|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Newpreston06.jpg|thumb|right|The small village of [[New Preston, Connecticut]] was one of the filming locations.]]\nPrincipal photography took place from October 3 and finished in November 1980, and primarily occurred in [[New Preston, Connecticut|New Preston]] and [[Kent, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bullsbridge.com/Friday_the_13th_Filmed_in_Kent.htm |publisher=Bullsbridge Inn|work=The Kent Good Times Dispatch; The Litchfield County Times|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 Set up Camp 30 Years Ago in Kent and New Preston, CT|author=Deakin, Bob|date=October 2004|accessdate=October 15, 2016}}</ref> Special effects artist [[Tom Savini]] was asked to work on the film but declined because he was already working on another project, ''[[Midnight (1982 film)|Midnight]]'' (1982).<ref name=bd>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3388837/13-fun-facts-friday-13th-part-2/|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|title=13 Fun Facts About \u2018Friday the 13th Part 2!\u2019|author=Thurman, Trace|date=May 1, 2016|accessdate=October 9, 2016}}</ref> In addition, he was not receptive to the concept of Jason as the killer in the film. Savini was then replaced by [[Stan Winston]]. Winston, however, had a scheduling conflict and had to drop out of the project.<ref name=bd/> The make-up effects were ultimately handled by Carl Fullerton. Fullerton designed the \"look\" for the adult Jason Voorhees and went with long red hair and a beard while following the facial deformities established in the original film in the make-up designed by Tom Savini for Jason as a child. Fullerton's look for the adult Jason was abandoned in the sequel, ''Friday the 13th Part 3'', despite the fact that the film took place the following day and was helmed by the same director, Steve Miner. Some fans have theorized that the sequence showing Jason with a beard and long hair reflects a \"dream\" rather than a reality because the following sequel picks up with the events showing his face having not happened, and therefore what was represented was Ginny's ''guess'' at what he looked like under the burlap sack rather than what he ''actually'' looked like, which would excuse the break in continuity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2015/08/the-continuity-issues-of-jason-voorhees.html|work=Friday the 13th: The Franchise|title=The Continuity Issues Of Jason Voorhees' Appearance Between Part 2 And Part 3|author=Parker, Jason|date=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012138/http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2015/08/the-continuity-issues-of-jason-voorhees.html|archive-date=October 18, 2018|access-date=February 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteve Daskawisz was rushed to the emergency room during filming after Amy Steel cut his hand with a machete.<ref name=bd/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2011/01/bts-wednesday-part-2-accident-and.html|title=Behind the Scenes: Part 2 accident and the Hospital|work=Friday the 13th: The Franchise|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018014208/http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2011/01/bts-wednesday-part-2-accident-and.html |archive-date=October 18, 2018|author=Parker, Jason|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref> Steel explained, \"The timing was wrong, and he didn't turn his pickaxe properly, and the machete hit his finger.\" Daskawisz received thirteen stitches on his middle finger. During the subsequent shoot, Daskawisz was forced to wear a piece of rubber over his finger, and both he and Steel insisted on reshooting this scene.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} During one take of Alice being killed by Jason, the ice pick prop didn't retract, injuring King.<ref name=bd/>\n\nIn one scene where Daskawisz was wearing the burlap flour sack, part of the flour sack was flapping at his eye, so the crew used tape inside the eye area to prevent it from flapping. Daskawisz received rug burns around his eye from the tape from wearing the rough flour sack material for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scabbyhorror.blogspot.co.uk/2009/01/whats-up-with-sack-head.html|work=Friday the 13th: The Ultimate Fan Blog|title=What's up with the sack head?|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> The use of the sack hood was similar to the 1976 film ''[[The Town That Dreaded Sundown]]''.{{sfn|Albright|2012|p=179}}\n\nThe scene where Steel's character gets grabbed from behind by an unmasked Jason in the climax took three takes to shoot it right. Steel was tense and frightened during filming of the scene.<ref name=bd/>\n\nRumors sparked that John Furey left before the film wrapped, as his character does not appear in the end. In truth, his character was not intended to have appeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lairofhorror.tripod.com/voorheeslair/dyk2.html|title=Friday The 13th Part 2: Did You Know?|publisher=Lair of Horror|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nLike its predecessor, ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' had difficulty receiving an R rating from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA).<ref name=clm/> Upon reviewing the film, the Classification and Rating Administration (CARA) warned Paul Hagger, an executive at Paramount, that the \"accumulation of violence throughout the film\" may still lead to an X rating even if substantial cuts were made.{{Sfn|Kendrick|2009|p=150}}\n\nA total of forty-eight seconds had to be cut from the film in order to avoid an [[X rated|X]] rating.<ref name=bd/>&nbsp;This film received a deluxe DVD release in February 2009, but the edited footage was not included. Most noted by censors was the murder scene of Jeff and Sandra, who are impaled by a spear while having sex in a bed (a scene many have compared to a scene in [[Mario Bava]]'s ''[[A Bay of Blood]]''), which the censors found particularly graphic.<ref name=bd/><ref name=clm>{{cite AV media|publisher=Image Entertainment |title=Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th|author=Farrands, Daniel|year=2013|type=Documentary}}</ref> After Paramount discovered actress Marta Kober was underage, a scene showing her with full frontal nudity was completely deleted.<ref name=bd/>\n\nOriginally, the film was supposed to end with Mrs. Voorhees' head opening her eyes and smiling towards the camera. However, Miner removed the scene out of the final film as he never seriously considered it for the film\u2019s actual ending. To this day, the footage of this alternate ending has yet to be released.<ref name=bd/>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical run===\nThe film was released theatrically on April 30, 1981, bringing in $6,429,784 its opening weekend. It played on 1,350 screens and would ultimately gross $21.7 million on a budget of $1.2 million. It was the 35th highest-grossing film of 1981, facing strong competition from such high-profile horror releases as ''[[Omen III: The Final Conflict]]'', ''[[The Evil Dead (1981 film)|The Evil Dead]]'', ''[[The Howling (film)|The Howling]]'', ''[[My Bloody Valentine (film)|My Bloody Valentine]]'', ''[[Happy Birthday to Me (film)|Happy Birthday to Me]]'', ''[[Graduation Day (film)|Graduation Day]]'', ''[[Halloween II (1981 film)|Halloween II]]'', and ''[[The Burning (film)|The Burning]]''.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|p=51}}\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' holds a 28% approval rating based on 43 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 4.46/10. The consensus reads: \u201c''Friday the 13th Part 2'' sets the template for the franchise to follow with more teen victims, more gruesome set pieces, and fewer reasons to keep following along.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/friday_the_13th_part_2/|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 (1981)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote that ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' is \"a cross between the Mad Slasher and Dead teenager genres; about two dozen movies a year feature a mad killer going berserk, and they're all about as bad as this one. Some have a little more plot, some have a little less. It doesn't matter.\"<ref name=\"Ebert\">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | title = Friday the 13th, Part 2 | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = January 1, 1981 | url = https://rogerebert.com/reviews/friday-the-13th-part-2-1981 | accessdate = February 11, 2015}}</ref> Helen Verongos of ''[[The Clarion-Ledger]]'' wrote: \"''Friday the 13th Part 2'' obviously does not pretend to be any more than it is, a cheap{{em dash}}dimestore cheap{{em dash}}thriller aimed at the adolescent market...&nbsp; It is designed to be predictable enough to make the average fourth-grader feel sharp-witted.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22052803/clarionledger/|work=[[The Clarion-Ledger]]|title=Horror of horrors: 'Friday the 13th' sequel nothing new|author=Verongos, Helen|date=May 8, 1981|p=14D|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nThe Dayton ''[[Dayton Daily News|Journal Herald]]''{{'}}s Terry Lawson deemed the film a \"special effects freak show for an audience immune to violence,\" and \"exploitative and gratuitous.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Dayton Daily News|The Journal Herald]]|location=Dayton, Ohio|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24618446/the_journal_herald/|title='Friday Part 2'|date=April 30, 1981|p=23|via=Newspapers.com|author=Lawson, Terry}} {{open access}}</ref> Jacqi Tully of the ''[[Arizona Daily Star]]'' praised the film's special effects, noting Jason as \"effectively disgusting sight,\" and ultimately summarizing: \"Gross is a pretty good way to describe it. Scary, bloody and violent come to mind, too. Also very effective.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|author=Tully, Jacqui|date=May 8, 1981|title='Friday the 13th' is gross, but let's not lose our heads|p=2|location=Tucson, Arizona|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15012259/fridaythe13thisgrossbutletsnotl/|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> Howard Pousner of ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' was less laudatory, deeming the return of the Jason Voorhees character as a \"ludicrous arrangement...&nbsp; before you know it, eight more people have been murdered in virtually every manner: a neck sliced by barbed wire, a skull smashed, a jugular macheteed ''[[sic]]'', a heart speared, et al.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|The Atlanta Constitution]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|author=Pousner, Howard|page=15-B|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24618689/the_atlanta_constitution/|date=May 8, 1981|title=Part 2 of This Nightmare Is 2 Too Many|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nWhen reviewing the film's Blu-ray release, David Harley of ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' said, \"It doesn't exactly stray far from the formula of the original film \u2014 neither do most of the other [[sequels]] \u2014 but ''Friday The 13th Part II'' still stands as an iconic and important entry in the series due to the introduction of Jason as the antagonist of the series and the usage of [[Cinema of Italy#Giallo .28Thriller.2FHorror.29|Italian horror]] films as an inspiration for its death scenes \u2014 most notably, the spear copulation death from [[Mario Bava]]\u2019s ''[[A Bay of Blood]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/16479/blu-ray-review-friday-the-13th-part-2/|title=Blu-ray Review: 'Friday the 13th Part 2' -|work=Bloody Disgusting!}}</ref> Scott Meslow of ''[[The Week]]'' described it as a transitional film that blended elements of the original film and those to come later in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/539067/friday-13th-part-2-how-young-franchise-took-first-steps-toward-creatinga-horror-icon|title=Friday the 13th Part 2: How a young franchise took its first steps toward creating a horror icon|last=Meslow|first=Scott|work=[[The Week]]|date=February 13, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018014135/http://theweek.com/articles/539067/friday-13th-part-2-how-young-franchise-took-first-steps-toward-creatinga-horror-icon|archive-date=October 18, 2018|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the film ranked at number one on a list of the 100 Greatest Slasher Movies on the genre website Vegan Voorhees.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.hudsonlee.com/the-100-greatest-slasher-movies-part-x-the-top-10/|title = The 100 Greatest Slasher Movies Part X|last = Lee|first = Hudson|publisher = |date =  April 23, 2014|website = Vegan Voorhees|accessdate = December 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Friday the 13th Part 2'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[Betamax]] by Paramount Home Video in 1981.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|oclc= 14346258|medium=[[VHS]]|year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|oclc=9672370|medium=[[Betamax]]|year=1981}}</ref> Paramount reissued the VHS again in 1994.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-0-792-10108-6|medium=[[VHS]]|year=1994|orig-year=1981}}</ref> The film was first released on [[DVD]] by Paramount on October 19, 1999, in a standard widescreen release featuring the theatrical trailer as the sole bonus feature.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-0-792-15881-3|medium=[[DVD]]|year=1999|orig-year=1981}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Paramount issued a \"deluxe edition\" of the film on both DVD and [[Blu-ray]], which included several documentary featurettes along with the theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-1-415-74714-8 |medium=[[DVD]]|year=2009|orig-year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-1-415-74718-6|medium=[[Blu-ray]]|year=2009|orig-year=1981}}</ref> In 2011, it was released in a 4-disc DVD collection along with the first, third, and fourth films in the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moviesunlimited.com/musite/product.asp?sku=D83927 |title=Buy Movies at Movies Unlimited - The Movie Collector's Site |work=moviesunlimited.com |accessdate=June 25, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414210057/http://www.moviesunlimited.com/musite/product.asp?sku=D83927 |archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref> It was again included in two Blu-ray sets: ''Friday the 13th: The Complete Collection'', released in 2013, and ''Friday the 13th: The Ultimate Collection'', in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3472385/new-friday-13th-blu-ray-collection-coming-next-year-full-details/|title=New 'Friday the 13th' Blu-ray Collection Coming Next Year; Full Details|author=Squires, John|date=November 30, 2017|accessdate=August 18, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701132008/https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3472385/new-friday-13th-blu-ray-collection-coming-next-year-full-details/|archivedate=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Friday the 13th Part 2\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Harry Manfredini]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 13, 2012 (La-La Land)<br>June 2015 (Waxworks)\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 43:02\n| label      = [[Gramavision Records|Gramavision]], La-La Land, Waxworks\n| producer   = Harry Manfredini, [[Jay Yuenger]], Neil S. Bulk\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nIn 1982, [[Gramavision Records]] released an [[LP album]] of selected pieces of Harry Manfredini's scores from the first three ''Friday the 13th'' films.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|p=94}} On January 13, 2012, La-La Land Records released a limited edition 6-CD boxset containing Manfredini's scores from the first six films. It sold out in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lalalandrecords.com/F13.html|title=La-La Land Records: Friday the 13th|publisher=La-La Land Records|accessdate=January 15, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115052539/http://www.lalalandrecords.com/F13.html|archivedate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> Waxworks Records released the [[Harry Manfredini]]-composed score on [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] in summer 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3332595/friday-13th-part-2-ost-coming-vinyl/|title=\u2018Friday The 13th Part 2\u2032 OST Coming To Vinyl|publisher=Waxworks Records|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Novelization ==\nA [[novelization]] based on the screenplay of Ron Kurz was published in 1988: Hawke, Simon, ''Friday the 13th Part II: A Novel'', New American Library, New York, 1988, {{ISBN|0-451-15337-5}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Brian|title=Regional Horror Films, 1958-1990|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0-786-47227-7|ref=harv|location=Jefferson, North Carolina}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bracke|first=Peter|title=Crystal Lake Memories|publisher=[[Titan Books]]|year=2006|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1-84576-343-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Kendrick, James|ref=harv|year=2009|title=Hollywood Bloodshed: Violence in 1980s American Cinema|location=Carbondale, Illinois|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|isbn=978-0-809-32888-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Friday the 13th Part 2}}\n* {{IMDb title|0082418}}\n* {{amg movie|18659}}\n* {{mojo title|friday13th2}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|friday_the_13th_part_2}}\n* [http://www.campcrystallake.com/thefilms/part2.htm Film page at the ''Camp Crystal Lake'' web site]\n* [http://fridaythe13thfilms.com/films/friday2.html Film page at Fridaythe13thfilms.com]\n\n{{Steve Miner}}\n{{Friday the 13th}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friday The 13th Part 02}}\n[[Category:1980s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s mystery films]]\n[[Category:1980s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1980s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:1980s slasher films|Friday Part 2]]\n[[Category:1981 films]]\n[[Category:1981 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steve Miner]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sean S. Cunningham]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harry Manfredini]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1979]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1984]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Friday the 13th (franchise) films|2]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about summer camps]]\n[[Category:Sequel films]]\n[[Category:1981 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = Friday the 13th Part 2\n| image           = Friday_the_13th_part2.jpg \n| caption         = Theatrical release poster\n| director        = [[Steve Miner]]\n| producer        = Steve Miner\n| writer          = {{plainlist|\n* Ron Kurz\n}}\n| based on        = {{Based on|Characters|[[Victor Miller (writer)|Victor Miller]]}}\n| starring        = {{plainlist| <!--PER BILLING BLOCK-->\n* [[Adrienne King]]\n* [[Amy Steel]]\n* [[John Furey]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Harry Manfredini]]\n| cinematography  = [[Peter Stein (cinematographer)|Peter Stein]]\n| editing         = Susan E. Cunningham\n| studio          = Georgetown Productions\n| distributor     = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released        = {{Film date|1981|4|30}}\n| runtime         = 87 minutes\n| country         = United States\n| language        = English\n| budget          = $1.2 million<ref name=numbers>{{cite web|url=https://the-numbers.com/movie/Friday-the-13th-Part-2#tab=summary|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 (1981)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150924091658/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Friday-the-13th-Part-2%23tab=summary|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross           = $21.7 million<ref name=numbers/>\n}}\n'''''Friday the 13th Part 2'''''{{efn|The film's poster and related marketing use the Roman numeral \"II\". However, the copyright notice and the film's on-screen title use \"Part 2\".}} is a 1981 American [[horror film]] produced and directed by [[Steve Miner]] in his [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]], written by Ron Kurz, and starring [[Amy Steel]] and [[John Furey]]. The film also features the return of [[Adrienne King]], [[Betsy Palmer]] and [[Walt Gorney]], who respectively portrayed [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]], [[Pamela Voorhees]], and [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Crazy Ralph|Crazy Ralph]] in the prior installment. It is the second installment in the [[Friday the 13th (franchise)|''Friday the 13th'' film series]] and a direct sequel to ''[[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' (1980). It picks up five years later, where a new murderer begins stalking the camp counselors at a nearby training camp on Crystal Lake.\n\nOriginally, ''Part 2'' was intended to be part of an [[Anthology film|anthology]] series of films based on the [[Friday the 13th|Friday the 13th superstition]]. However, after the popularity of the original film's surprise ending, the filmmakers opted to continue the story and mythology surrounding Camp Crystal Lake, a trend which would be repeated in every film in the franchise.\n\nLike the original film, ''Part 2'' faced opposition from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]], who noted its \"accumulative violence\" as problematic, resulting in numerous cuts being made to allow an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#MPAA film ratings|R]] rating. The film was released theatrically in North America on April 30, 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=friday13th2.htm|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121206025552/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=friday13th2.htm|archive-date=December 6, 2012}}</ref> Although it did not gross as much as the original, the sequel grossed $21.7 million in the U.S. on a budget of $1.2 million. A sequel, ''[[Friday the 13th Part III]]'', was released the following year.\n\n== Plot ==\nTwo months after [[Friday the 13th (1980 film)|the murders at Camp Crystal Lake]], sole survivor [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]] is recovering from her traumatic experience. In her apartment, when Alice opens the refrigerator to get her cat some food, she finds the severed head of [[Pamela Voorhees]] in her refrigerator and is murdered by an unknown assailant with an ice pick to her temple.\n\nFive years later, Paul Holt opens a school for camp counselors on the shore of Crystal Lake. The camp is attended by Sandra Dier, her boyfriend Jeff Dunsberry, troublemaker Scott Cheney, tomboy Terry McCarthy, wheelchair-bound Mark Jarvis, sweet-natured Vickie Perry, jokester Ted Bowen, and Paul's assistant [[Ginny (Friday the 13th)|Ginny Field]], as well as many other trainees. Around the campfire that night, Paul tells the counselors about the legend of [[Jason Voorhees]], of how he survived his drowning, grew up living in the woods, and is now seeking to kill any intruders to avenge his mother's death. A man with a spear scares everyone, but it's only Ted in a mask. Paul reassures everyone that Jason is dead and that Camp Crystal Lake is now condemned and off limits. That night, Crazy Ralph wanders onto the property to warn the group but is [[garrote]]d from behind a tree. The following day, Jeff and Sandra sneak off to Camp Crystal Lake and find a carcass before getting caught by Deputy Winslow and returned to the camp. Later, Winslow spots someone masked in a [[burlap sack]] running across the road and chases him into the woods and to a shack before he is killed with a hammer claw.\n\nBack at camp, Paul offers the others one last night on the town before the training begins; six stay behind, including Jeff and Sandra, who are forced to stay as punishment for sneaking off. At the bar, Ginny muses that if Jason were still alive and had witnessed his mother's death, it may have left him with no distinction between life and death, or right and wrong. Paul dismisses the idea, proclaiming that Jason is nothing but an [[urban legend]]. Meanwhile, the assailant appears at the camp and kills the counselors, one by one. Scott has his throat slit with a machete while caught in a rope trap, and Terry is killed off-screen upon finding his dead body. Mark gets the machete slammed into his face and falls down a flight of stairs. The killer then moves upstairs and impales Jeff and Sandra with a spear as they have sex, and then stabs Vickie with a kitchen knife.\n\nLater, Ginny and Paul return to find the place in disarray. In the dark, the killer ambushes Paul and continues to chase Ginny throughout the camp and into the woods, where she comes across the shack. After barricading herself inside, she finds an altar with Pamela Voorhees' head on it, surrounded by a pile of bodies. Realizing that Jason Voorhees is the killer, Ginny puts on Pamela's sweater and tries to psychologically convince Jason that she is his mother. The ruse fails when he spots his mother's head on the altar and attacks Ginny. Paul appears and attacks Jason, but he is quickly overwhelmed. Just as Jason is about to kill Paul with a pickaxe, Ginny picks up the machete and slams it down into Jason's shoulder, seemingly killing him.\n\nPaul and Ginny return to the cabin. They think that Jason has followed them, but when they open the door, they are greeted by Terry's dog, Muffin. Suddenly, an unmasked Jason bursts through the window from behind and grabs Ginny. She then awakens to being loaded into an ambulance. She calls out for Paul, who is nowhere to be seen, his fate left ambiguous. Back in the shack, Pamela Voorhees' head remains on the altar as Jason is also [[Friday the 13th Part III|nowhere to be seen]].\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Anchor|Warrington Gillette}}<!-- until an article is created for him -->\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Amy Steel]] as [[Ginny (Friday the 13th)|Ginny Field]]\n* [[John Furey]] as [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Paul Holt|Paul Holt]]\n* [[Adrienne King]] as [[Alice (Friday the 13th)|Alice Hardy]]\n* [[Steve Daskewisz]] as [[Jason Voorhees]]\n** Warrington Gillette as Jason Voorhees (unmasked)\n* [[Stuart Charno|Stu Charno]] as Ted Bowen\n* [[Lauren-Marie Taylor]] as Vickie Perry\n* Marta Kober as [[List of Friday the 13th characters#Sandra Dier|Sandra Dier]]\n* [[Tom McBride (actor)|Tom McBride]] as Mark Jarvis\n* [[Bill Randolph]] as Jeff Dunsberry\n* Kirsten Baker as Terry McCarthy\n* [[Russell Todd]] as Scott Cheney\n* [[Walt Gorney]] as [[Crazy Ralph]]\n* [[Betsy Palmer]] as [[Pamela Voorhees]]\n* Jack Marks as Deputy Winslow\n* Cliff Cudney as Max \n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nFollowing the success of ''Friday the 13th'' in 1980, [[Paramount Pictures]] began plans to make a sequel. First acquiring the worldwide distribution rights, Frank Mancuso, Sr. stated, \"We wanted it to be an event, where teenagers would flock to the theaters on that Friday night to see the latest episode.\" The initial ideas for a sequel involved the \"Friday the 13th\" title being used for a series of films, released once a year, that would not have direct continuity with one another but be a separate \"scary movie\" in their own right. Phil Scuderi\u2014one of three owners of Esquire Theaters, along with Steve Minasian and Bob Barsamian, who produced the original film\u2014insisted that the sequel have Jason Voorhees, Pamela's son, even though his appearance in the original film was only meant to be a joke. [[Steve Miner]], associate producer on the first film, believed in the idea and would go on to direct the first two sequels, after Cunningham opted not to return to the director's chair. Miner would use many of the same crew members from the first film while working on the sequels.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|pages=50\u201352}} Cunningham had mixed feelings about the entire \"Friday the 13th\" enterprise that he outlined for film critic and author [[Stephen Hunter]] in an interview for a book Hunter wrote on violent films. Hunter stated that Cunningham \"wasn't particularly proud\" of his work on these films, and Cunningham bluntly said that the only thing that seemed to reach a teenaged audience at that time involved high levels of gore and graphic violence.\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Adrienne King]] was pursued by an obsessed fan after the success of the original ''Friday the 13th'' and purportedly wished her role to be small as possible,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/how-friday-the-13th-star-adrienne-king-uses-her-terrifying-stalker-tale-to-help-her-fans/|title=Friday The 13th\u2019 Star Adrienne King Uses Her Terrifying Stalker Tale To Help Her Fans|publisher=Uproxx|author=Burns, Ashley|accessdate=September 30, 2016}}</ref> though in the documentary ''[[Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th]]'', it was stated that King's agent had asked for a higher salary, which the studio could not afford.<ref name=bd/>\n\nThe film's heroine, Ginny, is played by Amy Steel, who won the part through an audition. \"At the time of [making the film], it was before the genre really picked up so I didn\u2019t give it a lot of credit or take it seriously. For me, it was just another audition because I had no idea what it would end up meaning after all this time. When I played Ginny, I was really young and different from a lot of the people working at the time so that came out in my character. I was naturally suspicious of cocky guys at that age, and you see a lot of that when I\u2019m on screen with Paul (John Furey). I tried to put so much behind the actual words in the script just so she felt almost unreachable, to Paul and to audiences. I wanted her to have some power.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/16108/dread-central-s-final-girls-amy-steel/|work=Dread Central|author=Wixson, Heather|date=March 5, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012501/https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/16108/dread-central-s-final-girls-amy-steel/|archive-date=October 18, 2018|title=Dread Central\u2019s Final Girls: Amy Steel|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nActor Warrington Gillette played Jason unmasked at the end of the film. Stuntman Steve Daskawisz (also known as Steve Dash) was credited as Jason Stunt Double but played the masked Jason throughout the rest of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/3379/dash-steve-friday-the-13th-part-2/|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|author=Dash, Steve|work=Dread Central|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012354/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/3379/dash-steve-friday-the-13th-part-2/|archive-date=October 18, 2018|date=July 1, 2006|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Newpreston06.jpg|thumb|right|The small village of [[New Preston, Connecticut]] was one of the filming locations.]]\nPrincipal photography took place from October 3 and finished in November 1980, and primarily occurred in [[New Preston, Connecticut|New Preston]] and [[Kent, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bullsbridge.com/Friday_the_13th_Filmed_in_Kent.htm |publisher=Bullsbridge Inn|work=The Kent Good Times Dispatch; The Litchfield County Times|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 Set up Camp 30 Years Ago in Kent and New Preston, CT|author=Deakin, Bob|date=October 2004|accessdate=October 15, 2016}}</ref> Special effects artist [[Tom Savini]] was asked to work on the film but declined because he was already working on another project, ''[[Midnight (1982 film)|Midnight]]'' (1982).<ref name=bd>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3388837/13-fun-facts-friday-13th-part-2/|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|title=13 Fun Facts About \u2018Friday the 13th Part 2!\u2019|author=Thurman, Trace|date=May 1, 2016|accessdate=October 9, 2016}}</ref> In addition, he was not receptive to the concept of Jason as the killer in the film. Savini was then replaced by [[Stan Winston]]. Winston, however, had a scheduling conflict and had to drop out of the project.<ref name=bd/> The make-up effects were ultimately handled by Carl Fullerton. Fullerton designed the \"look\" for the adult Jason Voorhees and went with long red hair and a beard while following the facial deformities established in the original film in the make-up designed by Tom Savini for Jason as a child. Fullerton's look for the adult Jason was abandoned in the sequel, ''Friday the 13th Part 3'', despite the fact that the film took place the following day and was helmed by the same director, Steve Miner. Some fans have theorized that the sequence showing Jason with a beard and long hair reflects a \"dream\" rather than a reality because the following sequel picks up with the events showing his face having not happened, and therefore what was represented was Ginny's ''guess'' at what he looked like under the burlap sack rather than what he ''actually'' looked like, which would excuse the break in continuity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2015/08/the-continuity-issues-of-jason-voorhees.html|work=Friday the 13th: The Franchise|title=The Continuity Issues Of Jason Voorhees' Appearance Between Part 2 And Part 3|author=Parker, Jason|date=August 25, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018012138/http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2015/08/the-continuity-issues-of-jason-voorhees.html|archive-date=October 18, 2018|access-date=February 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteve Daskawisz was rushed to the emergency room during filming after Amy Steel cut his hand with a machete.<ref name=bd/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2011/01/bts-wednesday-part-2-accident-and.html|title=Behind the Scenes: Part 2 accident and the Hospital|work=Friday the 13th: The Franchise|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018014208/http://www.fridaythe13thfranchise.com/2011/01/bts-wednesday-part-2-accident-and.html |archive-date=October 18, 2018|author=Parker, Jason|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref> Steel explained, \"The timing was wrong, and he didn't turn his pickaxe properly, and the machete hit his finger.\" Daskawisz received thirteen stitches on his middle finger. During the subsequent shoot, Daskawisz was forced to wear a piece of rubber over his finger, and both he and Steel insisted on reshooting this scene.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} During one take of Alice being killed by Jason, the ice pick prop didn't retract, injuring King.<ref name=bd/>\n\nIn one scene where Daskawisz was wearing the burlap flour sack, part of the flour sack was flapping at his eye, so the crew used tape inside the eye area to prevent it from flapping. Daskawisz received rug burns around his eye from the tape from wearing the rough flour sack material for hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scabbyhorror.blogspot.co.uk/2009/01/whats-up-with-sack-head.html|work=Friday the 13th: The Ultimate Fan Blog|title=What's up with the sack head?|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> The use of the sack hood was similar to the 1976 film ''[[The Town That Dreaded Sundown]]''.{{sfn|Albright|2012|p=179}}\n\nThe scene where Steel's character gets grabbed from behind by an unmasked Jason in the climax took three takes to shoot it right. Steel was tense and frightened during filming of the scene.<ref name=bd/>\n\nRumors sparked that John Furey left before the film wrapped, as his character does not appear in the end. In truth, his character was not intended to have appeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lairofhorror.tripod.com/voorheeslair/dyk2.html|title=Friday The 13th Part 2: Did You Know?|publisher=Lair of Horror|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nLike its predecessor, ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' had difficulty receiving an R rating from the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA).<ref name=clm/> Upon reviewing the film, the Classification and Rating Administration (CARA) warned Paul Hagger, an executive at Paramount, that the \"accumulation of violence throughout the film\" may still lead to an X rating even if substantial cuts were made.{{Sfn|Kendrick|2009|p=150}}\n\nA total of forty-eight seconds had to be cut from the film in order to avoid an [[X rated|X]] rating.<ref name=bd/>&nbsp;This film received a deluxe DVD release in February 2009, but the edited footage was not included. Most noted by censors was the murder scene of Jeff and Sandra, who are impaled by a spear while having sex in a bed (a scene many have compared to a scene in [[Mario Bava]]'s ''[[A Bay of Blood]]''), which the censors found particularly graphic.<ref name=bd/><ref name=clm>{{cite AV media|publisher=Image Entertainment |title=Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th|author=Farrands, Daniel|year=2013|type=Documentary}}</ref> After Paramount discovered actress Marta Kober was underage, a scene showing her with full frontal nudity was completely deleted.<ref name=bd/>\n\nOriginally, the film was supposed to end with Mrs. Voorhees' head opening her eyes and smiling towards the camera. However, Miner removed the scene out of the final film as he never seriously considered it for the film\u2019s actual ending. To this day, the footage of this alternate ending has yet to be released.<ref name=bd/>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical run===\nThe film was released theatrically on April 30, 1981, bringing in $6,429,784 its opening weekend. It played on 1,350 screens and would ultimately gross $21.7 million on a budget of $1.2 million. It was the 35th highest-grossing film of 1981, facing strong competition from such high-profile horror releases as ''[[Omen III: The Final Conflict]]'', ''[[The Evil Dead (1981 film)|The Evil Dead]]'', ''[[The Howling (film)|The Howling]]'', ''[[My Bloody Valentine (film)|My Bloody Valentine]]'', ''[[Happy Birthday to Me (film)|Happy Birthday to Me]]'', ''[[Graduation Day (film)|Graduation Day]]'', ''[[Halloween II (1981 film)|Halloween II]]'', and ''[[The Burning (film)|The Burning]]''.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|p=51}}\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' holds a 28% approval rating based on 43 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 4.46/10. The consensus reads: \u201c''Friday the 13th Part 2'' sets the template for the franchise to follow with more teen victims, more gruesome set pieces, and fewer reasons to keep following along.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/friday_the_13th_part_2/|title=Friday the 13th Part 2 (1981)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote that ''Friday the 13th Part 2'' is \"a cross between the Mad Slasher and Dead teenager genres; about two dozen movies a year feature a mad killer going berserk, and they're all about as bad as this one. Some have a little more plot, some have a little less. It doesn't matter.\"<ref name=\"Ebert\">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | title = Friday the 13th, Part 2 | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = January 1, 1981 | url = https://rogerebert.com/reviews/friday-the-13th-part-2-1981 | accessdate = February 11, 2015}}</ref> Helen Verongos of ''[[The Clarion-Ledger]]'' wrote: \"''Friday the 13th Part 2'' obviously does not pretend to be any more than it is, a cheap{{em dash}}dimestore cheap{{em dash}}thriller aimed at the adolescent market...&nbsp; It is designed to be predictable enough to make the average fourth-grader feel sharp-witted.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22052803/clarionledger/|work=[[The Clarion-Ledger]]|title=Horror of horrors: 'Friday the 13th' sequel nothing new|author=Verongos, Helen|date=May 8, 1981|p=14D|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nThe Dayton ''[[Dayton Daily News|Journal Herald]]''{{'}}s Terry Lawson deemed the film a \"special effects freak show for an audience immune to violence,\" and \"exploitative and gratuitous.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Dayton Daily News|The Journal Herald]]|location=Dayton, Ohio|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24618446/the_journal_herald/|title='Friday Part 2'|date=April 30, 1981|p=23|via=Newspapers.com|author=Lawson, Terry}} {{open access}}</ref> Jacqi Tully of the ''[[Arizona Daily Star]]'' praised the film's special effects, noting Jason as \"effectively disgusting sight,\" and ultimately summarizing: \"Gross is a pretty good way to describe it. Scary, bloody and violent come to mind, too. Also very effective.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|author=Tully, Jacqui|date=May 8, 1981|title='Friday the 13th' is gross, but let's not lose our heads|p=2|location=Tucson, Arizona|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15012259/fridaythe13thisgrossbutletsnotl/|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> Howard Pousner of ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' was less laudatory, deeming the return of the Jason Voorhees character as a \"ludicrous arrangement...&nbsp; before you know it, eight more people have been murdered in virtually every manner: a neck sliced by barbed wire, a skull smashed, a jugular macheteed ''[[sic]]'', a heart speared, et al.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|The Atlanta Constitution]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|author=Pousner, Howard|page=15-B|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24618689/the_atlanta_constitution/|date=May 8, 1981|title=Part 2 of This Nightmare Is 2 Too Many|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nWhen reviewing the film's Blu-ray release, David Harley of ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' said, \"It doesn't exactly stray far from the formula of the original film \u2014 neither do most of the other [[sequels]] \u2014 but ''Friday The 13th Part II'' still stands as an iconic and important entry in the series due to the introduction of Jason as the antagonist of the series and the usage of [[Cinema of Italy#Giallo .28Thriller.2FHorror.29|Italian horror]] films as an inspiration for its death scenes \u2014 most notably, the spear copulation death from [[Mario Bava]]\u2019s ''[[A Bay of Blood]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/16479/blu-ray-review-friday-the-13th-part-2/|title=Blu-ray Review: 'Friday the 13th Part 2' -|work=Bloody Disgusting!}}</ref> Scott Meslow of ''[[The Week]]'' described it as a transitional film that blended elements of the original film and those to come later in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/539067/friday-13th-part-2-how-young-franchise-took-first-steps-toward-creatinga-horror-icon|title=Friday the 13th Part 2: How a young franchise took its first steps toward creating a horror icon|last=Meslow|first=Scott|work=[[The Week]]|date=February 13, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181018014135/http://theweek.com/articles/539067/friday-13th-part-2-how-young-franchise-took-first-steps-toward-creatinga-horror-icon|archive-date=October 18, 2018|access-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the film ranked at number one on a list of the 100 Greatest Slasher Movies on the genre website Vegan Voorhees.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.hudsonlee.com/the-100-greatest-slasher-movies-part-x-the-top-10/|title = The 100 Greatest Slasher Movies Part X|last = Lee|first = Hudson|publisher = |date =  April 23, 2014|website = Vegan Voorhees|accessdate = December 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Friday the 13th Part 2'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[Betamax]] by Paramount Home Video in 1981.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|oclc= 14346258|medium=[[VHS]]|year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|oclc=9672370|medium=[[Betamax]]|year=1981}}</ref> Paramount reissued the VHS again in 1994.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-0-792-10108-6|medium=[[VHS]]|year=1994|orig-year=1981}}</ref> The film was first released on [[DVD]] by Paramount on October 19, 1999, in a standard widescreen release featuring the theatrical trailer as the sole bonus feature.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-0-792-15881-3|medium=[[DVD]]|year=1999|orig-year=1981}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Paramount issued a \"deluxe edition\" of the film on both DVD and [[Blu-ray]], which included several documentary featurettes along with the theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-1-415-74714-8 |medium=[[DVD]]|year=2009|orig-year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|title=Friday the 13th Part 2|publisher=Paramount Home Video|isbn=978-1-415-74718-6|medium=[[Blu-ray]]|year=2009|orig-year=1981}}</ref> In 2011, it was released in a 4-disc DVD collection along with the first, third, and fourth films in the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moviesunlimited.com/musite/product.asp?sku=D83927 |title=Buy Movies at Movies Unlimited - The Movie Collector's Site |work=moviesunlimited.com |accessdate=June 25, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414210057/http://www.moviesunlimited.com/musite/product.asp?sku=D83927 |archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref> It was again included in two Blu-ray sets: ''Friday the 13th: The Complete Collection'', released in 2013, and ''Friday the 13th: The Ultimate Collection'', in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3472385/new-friday-13th-blu-ray-collection-coming-next-year-full-details/|title=New 'Friday the 13th' Blu-ray Collection Coming Next Year; Full Details|author=Squires, John|date=November 30, 2017|accessdate=August 18, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701132008/https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3472385/new-friday-13th-blu-ray-collection-coming-next-year-full-details/|archivedate=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Friday the 13th Part 2\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Harry Manfredini]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 13, 2012 (La-La Land)<br>June 2015 (Waxworks)\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 43:02\n| label      = [[Gramavision Records|Gramavision]], La-La Land, Waxworks\n| producer   = Harry Manfredini, [[Jay Yuenger]], Neil S. Bulk\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nIn 1982, [[Gramavision Records]] released an [[LP album]] of selected pieces of Harry Manfredini's scores from the first three ''Friday the 13th'' films.{{Sfn|Bracke|2006|p=94}} On January 13, 2012, La-La Land Records released a limited edition 6-CD boxset containing Manfredini's scores from the first six films. It sold out in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lalalandrecords.com/F13.html|title=La-La Land Records: Friday the 13th|publisher=La-La Land Records|accessdate=January 15, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115052539/http://www.lalalandrecords.com/F13.html|archivedate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> Waxworks Records released the [[Harry Manfredini]]-composed score on [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] in summer 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3332595/friday-13th-part-2-ost-coming-vinyl/|title=\u2018Friday The 13th Part 2\u2032 OST Coming To Vinyl|publisher=Waxworks Records|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Novelization ==\nA [[novelization]] based on the screenplay of Ron Kurz was published in 1988: Hawke, Simon, ''Friday the 13th Part II: A Novel'', New American Library, New York, 1988, {{ISBN|0-451-15337-5}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Brian|title=Regional Horror Films, 1958-1990|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0-786-47227-7|ref=harv|location=Jefferson, North Carolina}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bracke|first=Peter|title=Crystal Lake Memories|publisher=[[Titan Books]]|year=2006|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1-84576-343-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Kendrick, James|ref=harv|year=2009|title=Hollywood Bloodshed: Violence in 1980s American Cinema|location=Carbondale, Illinois|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|isbn=978-0-809-32888-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Friday the 13th Part 2}}\n* {{IMDb title|0082418}}\n* {{amg movie|18659}}\n* {{mojo title|friday13th2}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|friday_the_13th_part_2}}\n* [http://www.campcrystallake.com/thefilms/part2.htm Film page at the ''Camp Crystal Lake'' web site]\n* [http://fridaythe13thfilms.com/films/friday2.html Film page at Fridaythe13thfilms.com]\n\n{{Steve Miner}}\n{{Friday the 13th}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friday The 13th Part 02}}\n[[Category:1980s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s mystery films]]\n[[Category:1980s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1980s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:1980s slasher films|Friday Part 2]]\n[[Category:1981 films]]\n[[Category:1981 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steve Miner]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sean S. Cunningham]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harry Manfredini]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1979]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1984]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Friday the 13th (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about summer camps]]\n[[Category:Sequel films]]\n[[Category:1981 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friday_the_13th_Part_2"}
{"title_page": "The Courier (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Courier\n| image          = The Courier poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = Zackary Adler\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Edward Barker]]\n* Marc Goldberg\n* David Haring\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Zackary Adler\n* James Edward Barker\n* Andy Conway\n* Nicky Tate\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]]\n* [[Gary Oldman]]\n* [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]]\n* [[Alicia Agneson]]\n* Greg Orvis\n* [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]]\n* [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]]\n* [[Dermot Mulroney]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Michel Abramowicz]]\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* James Edward Barker\n* [[Tim Despic]]\n}}\n| editing        = Nick McCahearty\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* Grindstone Entertainment Group\n* Capstone Pictures\n* Signature Entertainment \n* Rollercoaster Angel Productions\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate]]\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States|2019|12|20|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/theatrical/the_courier|title=The Courier|website=[[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''The Courier''' is a 2019 [[action thriller film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/olga-kurylenko-to-star-in-female-led-action-thriller-the-courier-1203014815/|title=Olga Kurylenko to Star in Female-Led Action Thriller \u2018The Courier\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=30 October 2018}}</ref> directed by Zackary Adler, from a screenplay by Andy Conway and Nicky Tate. It stars [[Olga Kurylenko]], [[Gary Oldman]], [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]], [[Alicia Agneson]], Greg Orvis, [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]], [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]] and [[Dermot Mulroney]].\n\nThe film was released in the United States on November 22, 2019, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] and is scheduled to be released in the United Kingdom on December 20, 2019, by Signature Entertainment.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]] as The Courier\n* [[Gary Oldman]] as Ezekiel Mannings\n* [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]] as Nick Murch\n* [[Alicia Agneson]] as Agent Simmonds\n* Greg Orvis as The Sniper\n* [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]] as Agent Parlow\n* [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]] as Agent Bryant \n* [[Dermot Mulroney]] as Special Agent Roberts\n*[[Cally Taylor|Calli Taylor]] as Alys Mannings\n\n==Production==\nIn October 2018, it was announced [[Olga Kurylenko]] would star in the film, with [[Zackary Adler]] directing from a screenplay by Zackary Adler, James Edward Barker, Andy Conway and Nicky Tate, with Marc Goldberg and [[James Edward Barker]] producing under their Signature Films and Rollercoaster Angel Productions banner, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/olga-kurylenko-to-star-in-female-led-action-thriller-the-courier-1203014815/|title=Olga Kurylenko to Star in Female-Led Action Thriller \u2018The Courier\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Stewart|last=Clarke|date=October 30, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, [[Gary Oldman]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gary-oldman-joins-action-thriller-film-courier-1176200|title=Gary Oldman Joins Action-Thriller 'The Courier'|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Alex|last=Ritman|date=January 15, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In February 2019, [[Dermot Mulroney]], [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]], Amit Shah, [[Alicia Agneson]] and [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/dermot-mulroney-cast-the-courier-gary-oldman-olga-kurylenko-1202554483/|title=\u2018The Courier\u2019: Dermot Mulroney & More Join Gary Oldman, Olga Kurylenko In UK Indie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] began in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/dermot-mulroney-joins-olga-kurylenko-gary-oldman-in-uk-action-thriller-the-courier/5136862.article?referrer=RSS|title=Dermot Mulroney joins Olga Kurylenko, Gary Oldman in UK action thriller 'The Courier'|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe Courier was released in the United States on November 22, 2019, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-courier-trailer-gary-oldman-olga-kurylenko/|title=Exclusive: \u2018The Courier\u2019 Trailer Teases a Real-Time Thriller with Gary Oldman and Olga Kurylenko|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref> and in the United Kingdom on December 20, 2019, by Signature Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|title=The Courier|website=Launching Films|accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nReviews thus far have been negative.<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_courier_2019</ref><ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-courier</ref> A scathing [[Rex Reed]] in the ''[[The New York Observer|Observer]]'' named Oldman's performance the worst of his career, and said, \"In the moronic thriller ''The Courier'', nothing works on any level, but most of all where it matters most\u2014a script that makes sense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2019/11/the-courier-review-gary-oldman-rex-reed/|title=In 'The Courier', Gary Oldman Gives the Worst Performance of His Career|last=Reed|first=Rex|author-link=Rex Reed|date=November 21, 2019|website=[[The New York Observer|Observer]]|access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|9207616}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courier (2019 film), The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\u0628\u06cc\u06cc\u06cc\u06cc\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:British action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Courier\n| image          = The Courier poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = Zackary Adler\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Edward Barker]]\n* Marc Goldberg\n* David Haring\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Zackary Adler\n* James Edward Barker\n* Andy Conway\n* Nicky Tate\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]]\n* [[Gary Oldman]]\n* [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]]\n* [[Alicia Agneson]]\n* Greg Orvis\n* [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]]\n* [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]]\n* [[Dermot Mulroney]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Michel Abramowicz]]\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* James Edward Barker\n* [[Tim Despic]]\n}}\n| editing        = Nick McCahearty\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* Grindstone Entertainment Group\n* Capstone Pictures\n* Signature Entertainment \n* Rollercoaster Angel Productions\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate]]\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States|2019|12|20|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/theatrical/the_courier|title=The Courier|website=[[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''The Courier''' is a 2019 [[action thriller film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/olga-kurylenko-to-star-in-female-led-action-thriller-the-courier-1203014815/|title=Olga Kurylenko to Star in Female-Led Action Thriller \u2018The Courier\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=30 October 2018}}</ref> directed by Zackary Adler, from a screenplay by Andy Conway and Nicky Tate. It stars [[Olga Kurylenko]], [[Gary Oldman]], [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]], [[Alicia Agneson]], Greg Orvis, [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]], [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]] and [[Dermot Mulroney]].\n\nThe film was released in the United States on November 22, 2019, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] and is scheduled to be released in the United Kingdom on December 20, 2019, by Signature Entertainment.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]] as The Courier\n* [[Gary Oldman]] as Ezekiel Mannings\n* [[Amit Shah (actor)|Amit Shah]] as Nick Murch\n* [[Alicia Agneson]] as Agent Simmonds\n* Greg Orvis as The Sniper\n* [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]] as Agent Parlow\n* [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]] as Agent Bryant \n* [[Dermot Mulroney]] as Special Agent Roberts\n* Calli Taylor as Alys Mannings\n\n==Production==\nIn October 2018, it was announced [[Olga Kurylenko]] would star in the film, with [[Zackary Adler]] directing from a screenplay by Zackary Adler, James Edward Barker, Andy Conway and Nicky Tate, with Marc Goldberg and [[James Edward Barker]] producing under their Signature Films and Rollercoaster Angel Productions banner, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/olga-kurylenko-to-star-in-female-led-action-thriller-the-courier-1203014815/|title=Olga Kurylenko to Star in Female-Led Action Thriller \u2018The Courier\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Stewart|last=Clarke|date=October 30, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, [[Gary Oldman]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gary-oldman-joins-action-thriller-film-courier-1176200|title=Gary Oldman Joins Action-Thriller 'The Courier'|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Alex|last=Ritman|date=January 15, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In February 2019, [[Dermot Mulroney]], [[William Moseley (actor)|William Moseley]], Amit Shah, [[Alicia Agneson]] and [[Craig Conway (actor)|Craig Conway]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/dermot-mulroney-cast-the-courier-gary-oldman-olga-kurylenko-1202554483/|title=\u2018The Courier\u2019: Dermot Mulroney & More Join Gary Oldman, Olga Kurylenko In UK Indie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] began in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/dermot-mulroney-joins-olga-kurylenko-gary-oldman-in-uk-action-thriller-the-courier/5136862.article?referrer=RSS|title=Dermot Mulroney joins Olga Kurylenko, Gary Oldman in UK action thriller 'The Courier'|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe Courier was released in the United States on November 22, 2019, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-courier-trailer-gary-oldman-olga-kurylenko/|title=Exclusive: \u2018The Courier\u2019 Trailer Teases a Real-Time Thriller with Gary Oldman and Olga Kurylenko|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref> and in the United Kingdom on December 20, 2019, by Signature Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|title=The Courier|website=Launching Films|accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nReviews thus far have been negative.<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_courier_2019</ref><ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-courier</ref> A scathing [[Rex Reed]] in the ''[[The New York Observer|Observer]]'' named Oldman's performance the worst of his career, and said, \"In the moronic thriller ''The Courier'', nothing works on any level, but most of all where it matters most\u2014a script that makes sense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2019/11/the-courier-review-gary-oldman-rex-reed/|title=In 'The Courier', Gary Oldman Gives the Worst Performance of His Career|last=Reed|first=Rex|author-link=Rex Reed|date=November 21, 2019|website=[[The New York Observer|Observer]]|access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|9207616}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courier (2019 film), The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\u0628\u06cc\u06cc\u06cc\u06cc\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:British action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n", "name_user": "Hnaluru", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Courier_(2019_film)"}
